__data__.text: The first kafana, a type of bistro originating from the Ottoman period, was opened in Belgrade, Serbia, in the year 1522.
This kafana was located in Dorćol and served only Turkish coffee.
The Ottoman traveler Evliya Çelebi visited Belgrade in 1661 and reported the existence of 21 khans and 6 caravanserais.
The largest caravanserai, the Caravanserai of Sokollu Mehmed Pasha, had "160 chimneys".
Some caravanserais had harem sections.
The Austrians conquered Belgrade in 1718 and reported on the existence of kafanas in the city.
The Austrians named several kafanas, including "Crni orao", "Crveni petao", "Pet ševa", "Tri zeca", and "Divlji čovek".
The kafana "Kod dve bule" was notorious as the favorite place of the "debauched" Baron Franz von der Trenck.
In the 1717-1723 period, four breweries were opened in Belgrade.
The Austrian governor, Charles Alexander, Duke of Württemberg, was known for his love of the night life.
The Duke abolished all taxes on drink serving, causing business to blossom.
There were some 140 kafanas and pubs in the German section of the city.
Over 200 kafanas operated in the Serbian sector.
The kafanas in the German section mostly served beer.
The kafanas in the Serbian sector mostly served wine and rakia.

The English version of the word kafana appeared for the first time in 1615, published by George Sandys after his travels to Constantinople.

Zemun developed independently from Belgrade and belonged to different states for most of history.
Zemun became part of the same administrative unit as Belgrade on 4 October 1929.
Zemun lost its separate town status to Belgrade in 1934.
Zemun and Belgrade made a continuous built-up area since the 1950s.
The House at 10 Cara Dušana Street in Dorćol is usually named as the oldest house in Belgrade.
The White Bear Tavern is titled as the oldest house in Zemun.
The word "kafana" was introduced by the Ottomans and derived from the Persian qahvah–khanah, meaning "coffee house".
The English version of the word "kafana" appeared for the first time in 1615.
Prince Alexander Karađorđević codified hospitality objects in 1847.
He divided them into mehanas and khans, with former given the rank of craft shops.
Venues remained unchanged for a long time with clothless tables, loosen chairs and benches, tinplate furnaces fired by the guests themselves, tallow candles or petroleum lamps light.
A culture of spending hours in kafanas developed among the lower classes.
People discussed daily events, politics, shared funny stories or sang with gusle in kafanas.
Development of westernized venues began, built after the examples in Vienna or Budapest.
They became gathering spots for officers, clerks, landowners, and, unlike traditional kafanas, occasionally they had women guests.
Princess Ljubica Obrenović was a regular visitor of the fancy "Manojlova bašta", in modern Zeleni Venac.
"Manojlova bašta" was the first Belgrade's kafana to serve beer, starting in 1835.
Staying up late was against the law.
People would regularly stay in kafanas after-hours.
Belgrade had no street lights
Kafanas were establishments in Serbia that were categorized.
Kafanas of the first order were allowed to have one female waitress.
Kafanas became hubs of social life and diversified.
There were kafanas for craftsmen, farmers and traders, and leaseholders.
Some kafanas turned into debate clubs of political parties.
The kafana "Rajić" was the first to prepare modern ćevapčići around 1860.
Ćevapčići are a staple of Serbian cuisine and were popular in Belgrade.
The kafana "Rajić" was fully named "Kod Rajića junaka serbskog".
The kafana "Rajić" hosted the festivities after the withdrawal of the Ottomans from Belgrade in 1867.
The festivities were organized by Prince Mihailo.
The first hotel, "Kod jelena", was built in 1843.
The first hotel was later known as "Staro zdanje".
The first hotel introduced European tradition in entertainment.
The first hotel had the first ballroom in Belgrade.
The first ball in Belgrade was held in 1838.
Balls became more frequent after 1860 and had a strict timetable and etiquette.
The vogue of so-called "potato balls" spread among the lower classes.
"Potato balls" were named that way because people jumped and jerked as if they were kicking potato sacks.
The first kafana which allowed guests to stay the entire night was located across the Belgrade's Cathedral Church.
The kafana across the Cathedral Church allowed believers who remained long into the night in the churchyard to stay inside the kafana.
On 6 February 1893, the first electrified streetlamp was lit in the city.
Some chroniclers accept this as the moment when "proper night life" began.

Kafana "Amerika" was known for serving Turkish delight, chickpeas, and čočeks.
Kafana "Amerika" was notorious for introducing belly dancers and prostitution.
Hotel and restaurant "Balkan" was built in 1935 on the location of the former "Simina kafana" from 1860.
The "Balkan" was ranked as the highest category 1.
The "Balkan" was a meeting place of the businesspeople.
The "Balkan" was one of the few places where women were allowed to work.
"Zlatni krst", also in Terazije, was advertised in 1862 as having "12 rooms and stable for 30 horses".
The custom of unusual, exotic, and funny names for venues was common.
An example of this custom is "Pivni izvor" [Beer Spring].
An example of this custom is "Bosfor" [Bosporus], located next to "Dardaneli" [Dardanelles].
An example of this custom is "Engleska kraljica" [Queen of England].
An example of this custom is "Zemljotres" [Earthquake].

An example of this custom is "Kod bombardovanja Beograda" [Chez Bombing of Belgrade].
An example of this custom is "Gusarski brod" [Pirate Ship].
An example of this custom is "Dva panja" [Two Logs].
An example of this custom is "Jeftinoća" [Cheapness].
The Bibija stream was an administrative border between the Palilula and Dorćol quarters in Belgrade.
The Palilula quarter limited music to midnight.
People would jump across the stream in the Dorćol section to continue festivities when the music was limited in Palilula.
The "Velika Srbija" kafana was a popular nightlife spot in Belgrade.
The "Velika Srbija" kafana was demolished in 1901.
The National Museum in Belgrade was built on the site of the "Velika Srbija" kafana.
The clientele of the "Velika Srbija" kafana moved to Skadarlija after the kafana was demolished.
Skadarlija became the central nightlife point of Belgrade after the "Velika Srbija" kafana was demolished.
The "Tri šešira" kafana was founded in 1864 and is the oldest, still operational kafana in Skadarlija.
The "Tri šešira" kafana is the second oldest operational kafana in Belgrade.
The "Gospodarska Mehana" kafana was opened in 1820 and was closed in 2013.
The "Gospodarska Mehana" kafana was situated close to the mouth of the Topčiderka into the Sava.
The "Despotov Han" inn was the predecessor of the "Grčka Kraljica" kafana.
The "Despotov Han" inn holds the infamy as the first recorded brothel in Belgrade, dating from the 1840s.
Prostitution was always illegal in Belgrade.
The sex workers had to move to the streets while the venue continued as a regular kafana.
The last "officially unofficial" brothel from this period was located in the ground-floor house in the Čika Ljubina Street.
The house was demolished in the early 1990s.
The hotel was described as an "ornament" of the city with "equally beautiful interior and exterior".
The hotel was completely destroyed during the German bombing of Belgrade on 6 April 1941.
After the war, the state nationalized the lot where the hotel was located.
Despite several initiatives, the hotel was never rebuilt.
Restaurant "Park" was opened on the lot where the hotel was located.
The name of the restaurant's garden was the majority of the lot where the hotel was located.
The name of the restaurant was later changed to "Central Park".
The restaurant "Central Park" burned to the ground in December 2012.
In 1927, the Ministry of Finance of the Kingdom of the Serbs, Croats and Slovenes banned night life after 23:00.
Those who loiter and sit till the late hours, and it is past eleven, will be fined two dinars. This ban is known as the "tax for nighttime sitting".
It is considered the first official ban of night life in Serbia.
"Babuna" was an important kafana from this period.
"Babuna" was located in Senjak, across the modern Belgrade Fair.
The monument Pobednik, one of the most recognizable symbols of Belgrade today, was hosted in "Babuna" before it was erected on the Belgrade Fortress.
"Bajlonijeva kafana" was an important kafana from this period.
"Bajlonijeva kafana" was located in Skadarlija.
The owner of "Bajlonijeva kafana" was Ignjat Bajloni, a Czech émigré.
Ignjat Bajloni owned a brewery next to "Bajlonijeva kafana".
The air in "Bajlonijeva kafana" had the fresh hops aroma because of the brewery.
"Bajlonijeva kafana" was known for its beer: dark, light, golden,
The modern neighborhood and municipality Čukarica was named after a kafana called "Dva bela goluba" (Two White Doves).
"Dva bela goluba" was founded by Jovan Kujundžić, who was a tailor.
Originally, "Dva bela goluba" was a typical road meyhane.
The kafana "Dva bela goluba" became famous and the entire neighborhood and the modern Svetogorska Street were named after it in 1872.
In the late 1920s, the Artisan Guild purchased the house and the surrounding lot where "Dva bela goluba" was located.
The Artisan Guild planned to build the Home of the Artisans on the purchased location.
Jovan Kujundžić had a condition that the name "Dva bela goluba" should be preserved.
Above the entrance into the building of the Home of the Artisans, a sculptural composition was carved.
The sculptural composition depicts two persons with an anvil and scissors, and two white doves.
After the purchase of the house and the surrounding lot, the kafana "Dva bela goluba" moved to Skadarlija.
In the new building, finished in 1933, a restaurant was named "Zanatski dom".
There was a kafana named "Dva duda" (Two Pigeons) in Belgrade.
"Dva duda" was visited by Belgrade's coachmen and porters.
The kafana "Dva duda" was located close to Tašmajdan.
There was a kafana named "Era Gurman" in Belgrade.
"Era Gurman" was located at modern 6 Nikola Pašić Square.
The building of Belgrade City administration is located at the place where "Era Gurman" used to be.
"Era Gurman" was considered to have the best grilled and roasted meat in town.

The meyhane, a type of restaurant or tavern, was closed.

The house was declared a cultural monument of great value in 1979.
The name of the house is "Mostar".
The name "Mostar" was originally given to a small bridge (most) across the Mokroluški potok.
The Mokroluški potok is a stream that emptied into the Sava nearby.
The wooden bridge was regularly destroyed during the seasonal floods.
The kafana, a type of coffeehouse or restaurant, gave its name to the modern Mostar neighborhood and the large interchange.
The modern municipality New Belgrade was named that way in 1948.
"Novi Beograd" is a kafana that was opened in 1924 by Petar Kokotović.
The kafana "Novi Beograd" was originally located in the informal suburban settlement of Tošin Bunar.
"Nica" is a kafana that was located on the sandy beach across the Sava, in the modern Ušće in New Belgrade.
The kafana "Nica" was one of the favorite vacation spots during Interbellum.
People were transported from the city to the kafana by the small boats.
The kafana "Nica" was originally only one in the entire string of kafanas along the unurbanized bank.
The other kafanas along the unurbanized bank were named "Ostend", "Zdravlje", "Abadžija", "Jadran", "Krf", "Dubrovnik", and "Adrija".
The kafana "Nica" was the only one that survived construction of the King Alexander Bridge in the early 1930s.

The kafana "Takovo" was located across the Iguman's Palace in Terazije.
The "Takovo" kafana was a favorite place of the Liberals.
The "Beograd" cinema was later built on the location of the "Takovo" kafana.
The composer Stevan Mokranjac was a regular at the "Takovo" kafana.
The "Takovo" kafana had a good reputation among the city gentlemen.
The city gentlemen often visited the "Takovo" kafana for "intimate luncheons".
The kafana "Topola" was located at the central part of the modern Nikola Pašić Square.
The "Topola" kafana was popular among the lawyers.
The lawyers often visited the "Topola" kafana with their clients to write claims and complaints.
The first gas station in Belgrade was opened in 1926 in front of the "Topola" kafana.
The kafana at the former 1 Gospodska Street, later known as "Zeleni Venac", was established around 1840.
The kafana at "Zeleni Venac" had no name, but a tin-made green wreath hanging on the façade.
The name "Zeleni Venac" spread to the entire neighborhood.
The kafana at "Zeleni Venac" was demolished in the 1960s.
The kafana "Zlatna lađa" was built by wealthy merchant Miša Anastasijević.
The "Zlatna lađa" kafana was a meeting place of the merchants and prominent people during the reign of Prince Miloš.
The kafana "Zlatni krst" was located in Terazije.
The first cinema show in Belgrade was held in June 1896 at the "Zlatni krst" kafana.

The city of Belgrade has a history of hospitality and catering services, with many kafanas opened in a specific zone.
Some of the kafanas that were opened in this zone include "Kod zlatnog krsta", "Kod zlatnog točka", "Kod cara", "Kod zlatnog slona", and "Kod zlatnog sunca".
After World War II, nightlife in Belgrade dwindled due to the city's heavy damage, a reduced population, and a delayed establishment of a proper public transportation system.
In the 1950s-1960s, new kafanas became centers of nightlife and were often associated with sports clubs and stadiums, such as "Mladi Proleter", "Sinđelić", "Obilić", and "Stadion".
The clientele of these kafanas often included footballers and other athletes.
Another hub of nightlife in Belgrade was the riverbank kafanas held by fishermen, particularly in Zemun.
The popularity of entertainment and technological progress, such as the non-stop broadcast of Radio Belgrade and the Television Belgrade, impacted the importance of kafanas.
In the mid-1950s, the "Lotos Bar" was renovated and opened in Zmaj Jovina Street, offering an "artistic program" that included magicians, unicycle drivers, jugglers, fire eaters, and female dancers.
The "Lotos Bar" became an instant sensation and attracted members of the new Communist political establishment.
The "Lotos Bar" eventually became a not-so-hidden prostitution locale, leading to extended working hours and increased entry prices and drink costs.
Similar venues soon followed, including "Kristal Bar", bars in the "Mažestik" and "Metropol" hotels, and numerous striptease clubs in the 1990s.
By the early 2000s, all of these venues had closed.
Street prostitution developed in Belgrade in the late 1960s, with sex workers operating on the access roads to the Pančevo Bridge.
The restaurant is located in a building that was constructed in 1892 in Regensburg, Germany.
The building was originally built as a luxurious paddle steamer and was named Emperor Nicholas II.
The paddle steamer was used mostly for diplomatic missions, such as for the International Danube Commission.
The paddle steamer was part of the Kladovo transport in World War II.
After the war, the paddle steamer was renamed Split.
The Split was docked under the Branko's Bridge and was adapted into a restaurant.
The steerage of the Split was adapted into private rooms and was used for prostitution.
The police often raided the venue because it was used for prostitution.
The Split has been on a dry dock in Kladovo since 1992.
The Split was declared a cultural monument in 2006.
In Belgrade, kafanas evolved into westernized restaurants.
Despite the development of nightlife and the diversification of fun venues, Skadarlija remains a popular attraction in Belgrade.
Skadarlija is known as the main bohemian quarter of Belgrade.
Skadarlija twinned with Montmartre, a similar bohemian quarter in Paris, on 22 October 1977.
Skadarlija began to develop in 1830 with the settlement of Gypsies in the abandoned trenches in front of the ramparts.
Serbs and Turks also settled in Skadarlija after 1835.
An aqueduct was constructed in Skadarlija to conduct the stream of Bibijin Potok underground.
The largest arch of the aqueduct was named Skadar, and the street was named Skadarska Street after the arch.
The first khans, which were precursors of later kafanas, were built along the foothill of the wall after the aqueduct was built.

Skadarlija is a neighborhood in Belgrade, Serbia, known for its bohemian atmosphere.
The symbol of Skadarlija is a Fedora hat.
Fedora hats are mentioned in numerous folk songs, especially in the starogradska musical style.
Starogradska is a form of older urban folk music.
Skadarlija is known for its traditional Serbian restaurants.
The types of dishes on the menus in Skadarlija's restaurants include traditional Serbian food.
Skadarlija has a specific dress code, which includes uniforms and table clothes.
A certain type of music, specifically starogradska, is allowed in Skadarlija's restaurants.
Performers in Skadarlija's restaurants often know how to speak foreign languages.
Skadarlija is known for its bohemian lifestyle and has been a gathering place for artists and musicians.
Some performers in Skadarlija have become synonymous with the neighborhood, including Toma Zdravković, Silvana Armenulić, Olga Jančevecka, and Sofka Nikolić.
Sofka Nikolić was a popular singer in Skadarlija in the 1920s and 1930s.
Nikolić published dozens of records and became one of the most commercial female singers in Europe.
Musicians from Europe and the United States, including Josephine Baker, visited Nikolić in Skadarlija.
Nikolić was known as the "Queen of Skadarlija".
Nikolić withdrew from performing in 1939 after her young daughter, her only child, died.
Čubura is another neighborhood in Belgrade that is synonymous with bohemian life.
Čubura was once an outer village-turned-suburb, located along the Čuburski Potok stream.
Skadarlija and Čubura have some differences, including the clientele and the level of renovation in the neighborhoods.

The famed "Čuburska lipa" was demolished in early 2018.
A linden tree, planted in 1924 and brought from Lipik spa, was the namesake of "Čuburska lipa."
The linden tree was also cut down.
The kafana "Sokolac," located at the corner of Maksima Gorkog and Sazonova streets, was closed in 2017.
The kafana "?" was opened in 1823.

The menu of "?" has remained almost the same for 200 years.

The owner painted a question mark above the entrance, intending to change the name, but the name "?" stuck.
In 1834, the first pool table in Belgrade was installed in "?".
The kafana "Bled" was located in an early 20th century architectural ambience unit near the Jevremovac botanical garden.
"Bled" was one of the most famous fish restaurants.
"Bled" was closed in 2008 and reopened in 2018.
The kafana "Golf" was built on top of Košutnjak around 1930.
Dragiša Brašovan designed "Golf" as a rustic edifice with a cellar, ground floor, and a loft.
The main façade of "Golf" has 5 arched, glassed openings.
The middle opening of "Golf" serves as the door between the winter salon and summer garden.

The kafana, known as "Kolarac," was an elite venue where large balls in Belgrade were held. The clientele included military officers, high-ranking officials, politicians, artists, and members of various societies.
The Austrian, and later Austro-Hungarian, consulate was located in the same building as the "Kolarac" kafana from 1861 to 1878.
In 1896, the first Serbian intercity phone line was opened from "Kolarac" to the city of Niš.
After the "Kolarac" kafana was demolished, the kafana moved to Knez Mihailova Street.
"Lipov lad" was opened in 1928 and became trendy in the late 1950s as a meeting place for artists, actors, poets, and local bohemians. Later, it became a popular family venue.
In 1972, the entire neighborhood, including the old kafana, was reconstructed, but the linden trees which gave name to the kafana were preserved.
The neighborhood and one of the local communities of the Zvezdara municipality were named after the "Lipov lad" kafana.
"Madera" was built in 1937 on the location of the former kafana "Smederevo."
The name "Madera" comes from one of the guests who brought high-quality Madeira wine.

"Madera" became one of the most distinguished venues, known for its Bohemian clientele of athletes, journalists, and actors, called Maderaši (Aca Obradović, Predrag Milojević, Ljuba Tadić, Miroslav Radojčić, Dan Tana, Miljan Miljanić, Slavoljub Đukić, Dragoslav Šekularac).
The venue was massively refurbished in 2003.

The "Ruski car" venue is located in the Varoš Kapija area.
The "Ruski car" venue was popular among professors and students of the Belgrade University.
The "Ruski car" venue was opened in 1890.
The "Ruski car" venue was named after the assassinated tzar Alexander II of Russia.
The present building of the "Ruski car" venue was finished in 1926.
During the Interbellum, the "Ruski car" venue was a meeting place for the noble citizens and intellectual elite.
Communist authorities confiscated the building of the "Ruski car" venue after World War II.
The building of the "Ruski car" venue was nationalized in 1960.
The first Belgrade's "express restaurant", a self-serving buffet restaurant with cooked meals, was opened in the building of the "Ruski car" venue in 1960.
The name of the "Ruski car" venue was changed to "Zagreb" in 1960.
The original luxurious interior of the "Ruski car" venue was demolished and replaced with a simpler one.
Expensive cutlery of the "Ruski car" venue was replaced with plastic plates.
The name of the "Zagreb" venue was changed to "Vapiano" at some point.
The "Vapiano" venue was closed for renovation in 2017.
The "Vapiano" venue was reopened under the old name "Ruski car" in December 2019.
The "Srpska kafana" venue is situated close to the Atelje 212, at 25 Svetogorska Street.
The "Srpska kafana" venue was opened by merchant Luka Đurić in 1923.
Luka Đurić rented the "Srpska kafana" venue in 1924 when it was named "Kod Ere".
The building known as "Zlatno burence" is located in Prizrenska Street and was opened in 1866.
"Zlatno burence" was a gathering point for the Komite, members of the Serbian Chetnik Organization.
The venue was used as a recruitment center for volunteers in the Serbian-Turkish and Balkan Wars.
The original building of "Zlatno burence" was demolished in the early 1930s and replaced with a modern highrise.
The kafana is currently located near its original location at the corner where a stone barrel is placed as a symbol of the venue.
A popular but probably false anecdote is that Winston Churchill was beaten up in "Zlatno burence" while working as a journalist and writing bad reports on Serbs.
The Bermuda Triangle is a colloquial name for three rivaling kafanas in Makedonska Street.
At various points in time, all three kafanas in the Bermuda Triangle were closed, but two were later reopened.
The bohemian clientele of the Bermuda Triangle included city's best known artists, writers, actors, journalists, musicians, and city luminaries.
The name "Bermuda Triangle" emerged in the 1960s and was popularized in the early 1980s by the journalist Radmila Jovović.
Journalists of the nearby Politika gathered in "Grmeč", of the Radio Belgrade in "Pod Lipom", while "Šumatovac" was a neutral, joint territory.
The venues were known for one of the symbols of the old-style Serbian kafanas: red-white checkered tablecloths.
"Grmeč" was originally a beer hall named "Kod Muse" and was opened by the Lazić family in the mid-1930s.
During the yard works for "Grmeč", a Roman sarcophagus with the body of a centurion and pieces of sacral jewelry were discovered.

A restaurant was opened in the new building.

Another well-known venue, "Atina", was situated in Terazije.

The popularity of "Atina" was especially boosted in the 1970s and the 1980s.

The buffet was always filled with interesting faces.

The interiors of the buffet remained unchanged from the 1960s and 1970s.

The kafana "Tri lista duvana" was founded in 1882 at the corner of Bulevar Kralja Aleksandra and Kneza Miloša Street.
In 1883, the first phone line in Serbia, which was 300 m long, was conducted at the "Tri lista duvana" kafana.
The building of the "Tri lista duvana" kafana was demolished in 1989 to make way for the Hilton Hotel.
The Hilton Hotel was never built on the location where the "Tri lista duvana" kafana was demolished.
The kafana "Vidin kapija" was opened in 1861 at the corner of modern Palmotićeva, Hilandarska and Džordža Vašingtona streets.
The original name of the "Vidin kapija" kafana is unknown.
In 1864, the name of the "Vidin kapija" kafana was changed to "Kod sedam hrabrih Švaba" after German contractors were given the job of building the neighboring First Town Hospital.
A drawing of seven drunk Germans chasing a rabbit was above the door of the "Kod sedam hrabrih Švaba" kafana.
The "Kod sedam hrabrih Švaba" kafana was closed during the German occupation in World War II.
Regular visitors of the "Vidin kapija" kafana included Đura Jakšić, Branislav Petronijević and Vojislav Ilić.
After the war, the "Vidin kapija" kafana was reopened in the late 1950s.
The "Vidin kapija" kafana was closed in the mid-2000s.
The ultra-modern club "Medžik" was designed by Karim Rashid and opened on the location of the "Vidin kapija" kafana.
The club "Medžik" was closed a few years after it was opened.
Historian Dubravka Stojanović considers kafanas as the first institute of the new society in terms of chronology and importance.
No "invitation" was needed to enter kafanas, making them the first democratic space.
Kafanas served as gathering places and recruitment centers for numerous wars and rebellions.
The kafana "Crni Konj" was a recruitment center for individual fighters in the Serbian-Ottoman Wars.
The kafana "Kragujevac" was a gathering place for Garibalidians, Italian volunteers in the Serbian-Turkish Wars of 1876-1878.
The kafana "Zlatni Krst" was a recruitment center for Serbian volunteers for the Serbian-Turkish Wars of 1876-1878.
Kafanas were the first public places for drafting contracts and merchant treaties.
Kafanas developed around the main merchant areas and old khans.
Kafanas allowed poor classes to participate in economic activities.
The "Zisina kafana", opened before 1826 in Savamala, was one of the first kafanas in Belgrade.
"Kod Paje kantardžije" and nearby "?" were also important kafanas in Belgrade.
The first bank in Belgrade, the First Serbian Bank, was located in the "Staro Zdanje" kafana.
The first exchange office in Belgrade was located in a kafana.
The first labor market in Belgrade was located in a kafana.
The first stock exchange in Belgrade was located in the "Bosna" kafana.
The first insurance office in Belgrade was located in a kafana.
The first private medical office in Belgrade was located in a kafana.
The first photographic studio in Belgrade was located in a kafana.
Every guild had "its own" kafana.

The Lumière brothers' camera is kept at the Yugoslav Film Archive in Belgrade.
In 1896, the first intercity phone line was established between "Kolarac" in Belgrade and the city of Niš.
On the Belgrade side of the phone line, there was a concert of the vocal ensemble "Stanković".
On the Niš side of the phone line, there was a singers' society "Branko".
In 1900, travelling cinemas began to show movies in "Kasina".
The first permanent cinema was opened in Belgrade in 1910, in "Kasina".
In the 1900s, "Kolarac" was a regular meeting place of young officers headed by Dragutin Dimitrijević Apis.
In "Kolarac", Dragutin Dimitrijević Apis and the young officers plotted the 1903 May Coup.
The 1903 May Coup ended with the deaths of king Alexander and queen Draga.
The 1903 May Coup terminated the Obrenović dynasty in 1903.
The first book fair in Belgrade was held in "Kolarac".
In the 1900s, the first individual public clock in Belgrade was placed in front of the "Kod Albanije".
In 1905, the elementary school "Karađorđe" was established in the "Gavrilović".
The "Gavrilović" operated as a school by day and as a kafana in the afternoon and evening.
In the same period, the elementary school "Jovan Cvijić" was established and operated in a similar manner with the "Lavadinović" kafana.
In the 1910s, members of the revolutionary movement Young Bosnia gathered in the "Zlatna Moruna".
In the "Zlatna Moruna", members of the revolutionary movement Young Bosnia planned their actions, including the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria in 1914
Public reaction to rock and roll in Yugoslavia in the late 1940s and early 1950s lacked disputes and rage.
Older generations in Yugoslavia did not perceive rock and roll, nor the accompanying way of dancing or dressing as a problem.
By this time, Yugoslavia was more open to foreign influences compared to other Communist states.
Citizens of Yugoslavia freely travelled abroad.
No one stopped the creation of numerous rock bands in Yugoslavia, called vokalno-instrumentalni sastavi, or VIS ("vocal-instrumental band").
The penetration of rock and roll in Yugoslavia was slow at first.
Nikola Karaklajić was a pioneer promoter of rock and roll in Yugoslavia.
Karaklajić was a chess master and editor at Radio Belgrade.
Karaklajić's TV show "Concert for crazy young people" was the most popular.
The TV show premiered in January 1967 and was aired once a month until 1969.
Another popular TV show in Yugoslavia was "Maksimetar" (1970-1972).
Among the printed media in Yugoslavia, the most influential was "Džuboks", which debuted on 3 May 1966.
Entry in the clubs in Yugoslavia was free or the fees were symbolic.
Some clubs had passes, but they were easily obtained.
Security guards had great latitude letting someone in to the clubs.
People were searched and checked whether they were underage or intoxicated.
First clubs in Yugoslavia were small and located in private houses and apartments.
City authorities were bent on closing the clubs.
"Euridika" was a predecessor of the future disco clubs in Yugoslavia.
The club opened in Vračar, in a private house at 33 Molerova Street in 1961.

Lord Snowdon was announced to attend an event. However, he did not show up.
The event was held at a venue located at 17 Ive Lole Ribara Street, which is now Svetogorska, in Jevrem Grujić's House in Stari Grad.
The venue was near the Atelje 212 theatre.

At the opening of the venue, almost the entire acting troop of Atelje 212 was present, as well as dramatists, authors, and painters, including Mira Trailović, Jovan Ćirilov, Ivan Tabaković, and Dušan Matić.
The disco was founded by Lazar Šećerović, a translator, bon vivant, and direct descendant of Jevrem Grujić.
At the time of the opening, other discos existed only in Paris, London, and Milan.
The famous Studio 54 in New York City was opened 10 years after this disco.
The working hours of the disco were from 18:30 to 1:00.
The music played at the disco was mostly soul, including artists such as Aretha Franklin, Otis Redding, The Temptations, and Dusty Springfield.
The venue was small and situated in the basement.
The disco was hailed as a major improvement in the nightlife offer in the city and was credited with "democratization of fun".
The club introduced several "firsts", such as allowing girls without male companions, people dancing alone, and after parties when selected groups would move to the upper floor for more quiet fun.
The club was also called "Lola", after the street.
The disco was the "only disco between Trieste and Vladivostok".

Members of the international jet-set visited the club, including Pierre Cardin, Paco Rabanne, Catherine Deneuve, Judi Dench, Nina Ricci, Omar Sharif, Marisa Berenson, Alain Delon, and Claudia Cardinale.
Rock bands practiced in the club during the day.

The first venue of its kind was established in Yugoslavia and the wider region of Communist ruled states, called KST (Klub studenata tehnike).
KST was unofficially established in 1952 for the students of three technical faculties: architecture, electrical engineering, and civil engineering.
KST was located in a laboratory, almost in the basement, at 73 Bulevar Revolucije, which is now Bulevar Kralja Aleksandra.
High School for Technical Engineering, to which the faculties were subordinated at the time, made KST official in March 1954.
The club was used both for studying and dance parties.
The disco section of KST was opened on 29 February 1968.
Originally, KST had only one magnetophon.
The music played at KST was various, including funk, soul, disco, rock and roll, twist, waltz.
KST promoted young musicians and some of the most important Yugoslav rock-groups performed here in their early days, like Riblja Čorba, Poslednja Igra Leptira, Haustor, and Partibrejkers.
The first "unplugged" concert in the Balkans was performed at KST by the Bijelo Dugme.
Many groups recorded albums at KST.
KST became "another house" for musicians and the club which "makes DJs".
The club also organized theatrical and poetry evenings, freshmen welcome parties, fashion shows, and the famous pre-New Year's Eve masquerade balls.
Performers at KST included greatest stars of Serbian acting, like Ljuba Tadić, Olivera Marković, Snežana Savić, Tanja Bošković, Petar Kralj, and Ljuba Moljac.
The venue also became an important place for public debates and discussions.

Kafanas adapted for the youth did not exist.
There were several dance halls where "better bands" performed.
The rest of the venues organized "typically dilettante and irresponsible" dance parties.
Only a few places had jukeboxes or other "automated musical machines".
The most popular disco clubs were "Youth Center", "Go-Go Dancing" in Tašmajdan and "Disco Club 202" in the old synagogue in Zemun.
All youth venues had expensive tickets.
Later in the 1970s, Belgrade began to resemble other world metropolises.
Numerous internationally important events developed in Belgrade.
Regarding night life, fashion or music, everything was generally toned down from the wild 1960s.
Major influence came from Western Europe, mainly through Italy.
Rock and roll was especially popular.
By the mid-1970s, disco clubs turned into the exclusive venues.
The entry fees became too high, though some included a drink.
Drinks, in general, also became expensive.
Various inspection rarely visited the venues.
Visitors smuggled alcohol into the clubs.
The largest crowds were during weekends.
The clubs were open during the entire week.
The clubs usually had only one non-working day, varying from club to club.
Working hours mostly didn't extend after 2 a.m.
In order to avoid the intent of the authorities to close them, the clubs secured patronage of some state-owned institution.
The clubs were registered as the "restaurants with music".

It was planned as the standing bar for quick drinks, so it had no chairs.

The venue called "Cepelin" had blacklights and a projector that emitted psychedelic music videos on the walls, which were mostly black.
The rooms in "Cepelin" were stuffy, and the colors of the lights changed depending on the DJ who was working that night.
Parts of the walls and furniture in "Cepelin" were in red, with colorful flower prints.
DJ Mister Čupko was a popular person in "Cepelin".
The main bouncer in "Cepelin", known as Oumpah-pah, had head-to-toe tattoos.
Đorđe Božović Giška and his entourage were regular visitors in "Cepelin".
"Cepelin" was located next to the Fifth Gymnasium and was sponsored by the Tašmajdan Sports and Recreation Center.
Saša Nikolić opened "Cepelin".
"Cepelin" had working hours of 16:00-21:00 (matinée, for the minors) and 21:00-24:00, for adults.
Minors were not allowed to stay during the later program in "Cepelin".
DJs, including Saša Radosavljević and Raša Petrović, were located in the glass booth above the dance podium in "Cepelin".
"Cepelin" was renovated and expanded in the mid-1970s and included live performances from the most popular Yugoslav rock bands.
The most frequent performers in "Cepelin" were the Korni Grupa.
"Cepelin" was closed in 1980, citing renovation.
When "Cepelin" was reopened, it was a different venue, renamed to "Taš".
Akvarijus was the only one which could attract some of the "Cepelin" visitors.

In February 1990, Kristijan Golubović, along with Dragan Nikolić Gagi, raided the venue where everyone was forced to lay on the ground and firing rapid fire into the ceiling. The venue was "Monokl".
"Monokl" was opened in the bohemian Skadarlija, across the kafana "Tri šešira".
Silvana Armenulić performed at the opening of "Monokl".
Maksa Ćatović was the disc jockey at "Monokl". Previously, he was a disc jockey in "Cepelin".
"Resnik" was opened in the suburb of Resnik.
"Resnik" was opened in the former adult movie theater which was closed by the authorities.
"Resnik" wasn't much attended as it was distant from downtown.
By this time, DJ's had become stars in their own right.
The most popular DJ was Zoran Modli.
"Akademija" club was opened at 53 Knez Mihailova Street, in the dark basement of the Gallery of the Painting Academy.
"Akademija" was opened at the end of 1981.
"Akademija" was a rock and roll venue.
"Akademija" was a meeting place of the rockers, artists, politicians' children, young and avant-garde rebels, etc.
The original line-up of Ekaterina Velika gathered here. The members were Milan Mladenović, Margita Stefanović, and Bojan Pečar.
Other musicians who performed at "Akademija" included Električni Orgazam, Partibrejkers, Psihomodo Pop, and Toni Montano.
Visitors of the elite discos avoided "Akademija" completely as it was considered a "hole which shocks and provokes".
"Akademija" was an important part in the growing up and maturing of generations to come and survived until 2011.

The "Duga" club was opened in 1981 in Zvezdara.
The "Duga" club was originally a rearranged basement of a private house.
Over 200,000 Deutsche Marks were spent on adapting the "Duga" club.
The adaptation of the "Duga" club was done by architect Ilija Gligorijević.
An average, rich customer would spend as much in the "Duga" club per night as a factory worker earns in a year.
Legendary actor Zoran Radmilović would regularly visit the "Duga" club in slippers for a coffee.
Zoran Radmilović lived in the vicinity of the "Duga" club.
JAT is a company that had one of the first barges.
The JAT barge was originally intended only for the employees of the JAT Airways.
The JAT barge became a gathering place for regular clientele and was considered a famous venue in the city.
The JAT barge was derelict by the 2000s.
The JAT barge was sold to a private owner in the 2000s.
Before the JAT barge was renovated, it detached and was taken by the river downstream.
The owner of the JAT barge took emergency measures to keep it afloat.
In January 2019, the JAT barge sank under the heavy snowfall.
The river barge itself was considered one of the best, produced in Smederevo.
"Bezistan" was a disco club in Terazije.
"Bezistan" was different from other discos of the era and was the only "dancing club" in the city.
The popularity of the Italo disco reached Belgrade in the mid-1980s.
"Bezistan" organized dance competitions for participants from the entire Yugoslavia.
Band Zana was promoted in "Bezistan".

The first splavovi opened for visitors originated in the late 1970s.
The first restaurant named "Argument" was opened in 1983.
Barge "Blek Pantersi", owned by the music band of the same name, was opened in 1990.
The splavovi experienced a boom after 1991.
By the 2010s, there were over 200 cafes, restaurants, kafanas, and discos on the barges.
The first splavovi on the Sava Quay were opened in the summer of 1996.
The barges in Staro Sajmište were the first where "urban" splavovi appeared.
The entire sub-culture originating in the venues became mainstream.
The constant public conflict between the cheap fun and criminal on the barges, and the solemnity of the neighborhood given its war history as a Sajmište concentration camp, continued for decades.
All barges were moved out of Staro Sajmište by the late 2010s.
The splav "Hua Hua" opened in 1983, close to the northern tip of Ada Ciganlija.
"Hua Hua" was the most popular splav in the 1980s.
The venue "Hua Hua" was sold in 2013.
"Savski Galeb" opened in 1987, it was the first such facility on the Sava Quay, in Blokovi.
"Savski Galeb" was an adapted old freight barge.
The 1990s in Serbia were marked with calamities: break-up of Yugoslavia, wars, economic sanctions, collapse of the standard of living.
Criminals began occupying the clubs and nightlife in general.
Fashion and aesthetics of the turbo-folk became a norm.
Shootings and killings in disco clubs became regular events.

The first barge with a DJ, a separated dance floor, and booths for sitting was well visited since its opening.
This barge was originally visited by "roamers" from all over the city.
With the general criminalization of society, it became the gathering point for members of criminal clans from Zemun and New Belgrade.
Nana, located at 3-a Koste Glavinića Street in Senjak, was originally an elegant little nightclub.
Nana had a more urban and sophisticated atmosphere than "Duga".
During its "sophisticated" days, Nana did not play folk music.
Nana was a favorite place of foreign diplomats before criminals began to gather in it.
Nana had a dress code, requiring suits since 1987.
Criminals discovered and gathered in Nana, organizing in local clans.
The first murder in Nana occurred on 24 March 1990, when Andrija Lakonić Laki was killed.
Laki was unofficially claimed to be a police snitch.
Darko Ašanin and Vesko Vukotić were accused of the murder.
The trial for Laki's murder involved many criminals and policemen, including inspector Miroslav Bižić.
Bižić was accused of hiding evidence and helping Vukotić flee the country.
The case was never closed.
Bižić was assassinated in 1996, and Ašanin was murdered in June 1998.
These crimes remained unsolved.
Nana was closed and later reopened, but it became a "place to be avoided".
On 17 December 2017, Aleksandar Savković, a member of the FK Rad's supporter group, was killed in front of the club, and another person was wounded.

The club named "Industrija" was located at 19 Vasina Street.
"Industrija" played only electronic music.
"Industrija" is described as a place with "numerous fairytales, myths and truths" told about it.
The venue later hosted the "Ilegala" café.
Today, the location of "Industrija" is a bakery.
"Industrija" is described as "writing the history of the Serbian electronic scene" and the "place where everything started".
"Industrija" was opened in 1994 in the former boiler room of the Philosophy Faculty.
DJs of the developing electronic music included Deki S.T.R.O.B., Mark Wee, Vlada Eye, Velja Innvision, Gordan Paunović, Vlada Janjić, Boža Podunavac, X-periment, TTP, and Sugardaddy O.
Despite international sanctions imposed on Serbia at the time, foreign DJs performed 2-3 times a month at "Industrija".
Some of the foreign DJs who performed at "Industrija" included Moby, Mark EG, and DJ Hell.
"Underground" was a club located in the cave below the Belgrade Fortress.
"Underground" was known for the specific type of music: acid jazz, funk, drum and house.
"Underground" enjoyed a cult status for years.
After the change of proprietors, the choice of music at "Underground" also changed and the club began playing folk music.
"Underground" was later closed.

There were other clubs in Belgrade, including "Apartman" at 43 Karađorđeva Street, "Batler" and "Francuska Sobarica" at 12 Francuska Street, "Bordel" at 6 Gospodar Jevermova Street, "Buha" in the building of the Boško Buha Theatre on the Republic Square, "Bus" in Tašmajdan,
The "Magna House" is located at 9 Dragoslava Jovanovića Street and has been the location of the restaurant "Gradonačelnik" since 1998.
The "Omen" techno rave club is located at 16 Obilićev Venac Street.
The "Omen" club is known for its small size and intimate atmosphere.
Pinball machines are located at the entrance of the "Omen" club.
"Pećina" is situated at the entry into the Tašmajdan's lagums beneath the park.
The "Pećina" location has been the site of the "Ovo je moj grad" festival.
"Sara" is a barge on Ada Ciganlija.
"Sara" was the first venue with solely electronic music.
"Sara" was opened only for a year in 1994.
"Soul Food" is located at 6 Francuska Street.
"Soul Food" is usually labeled as the "first club with strictly defined concept, shaped by the dance music".
The clientele of "Soul Food" mostly moved to "Industrija" after its closure in 1997.
"F6" and later "Dot" are disco clubs with completely different musical direction.
"Triton" is a splav (a type of floating nightclub).
"Triton" was one of the most popular venues at the time.
"Triton" originally functioned as a "disco on the water".
"Triton" was the location of numerous shootouts.
"Trozubac" is located between the city's central square Terazije and Nušićeva Street.
"Trozubac" was a gathering place of the criminals.
"Tube" is located at the corner of the Simina and Dobračina streets.
